Mars Hill Summer Camp
description: A summer road cycling camp in the mountains of Western North Carolina geared for aspiring junior and collegiate racers, whether new to racing, ready to make the next step up, or prepping for upcoming Road Nationals.
course: Rides at camp utilize the nearby TT and RR courses for the 2016 Collegiate Road Nationals; climbs up the Blue Ridge Parkway to Mt. Mitchell, the highest peak in the East; track workouts at Asheville's Mellowdrome; and a variety of lightly traveled back roads in the Blue Ridge Mountains.
notes:
WHERE: Camp will be based at Mars Hill University’s beautiful campus nestled in the heart of the Blue Ridge Mountains. The college provides immediate access to an amazing network of lightly traveled roads, including extended climbs, rolling terrain, and flat/fast rides along the river. Situated in Madison County (“The Jewel of the Blue Ridge”) Mars Hill’s neighbors include the Blue Ridge Parkway, Mt. Mitchell State Park, Pisgah National Forest, the Appalachian Trail, and the French Broad River. Mars Hill is just 18 miles north of vibrant Asheville, NC.

WHEN: Two sessions this year! Session 1 is June 12-17. Session 2 is June 18-23. Or you can do both and stay the entire time.

Session 1: Drop Off: Sunday, June 12th 1-2pm. Pick Up: Friday, June 17th: 11am.

Session 2: Drop Off: Saturday, June 18th 1-2pm. Pick Up: Thursday, June 23rd at 11am.

WHO: Aspiring road racers ages 10-collegiate. Cyclists will be grouped based on experience, ability, and skill level. All cyclists must have prior group riding experience (racing isn’t required) and a current USA Cycling license. Parents are welcome.

BENEFITS:
• Riding in the beautiful mountains.
• All meals and training fuel provided.
• PowerTap wheels to demo.
• Free official Mars Hill University team jersey (If registered by April 18)
• USAC upgrade points for attending camp: 3pts if upgrading from 4-3
• Led by USAC certified coaches, national champions, and professionals.

TOPICS COVERED:
• Race strategy and tactics for individuals and teams
• Skills and bike handling sessions
• Racing and training with a power meter
• Endurance training plans and goal setting
• Race preparation, fueling, and recovery
• Aerodynamics, power-to-weight, and equipment selection
• Mechanics workshop covering maintenance and basic repair
• Core strength, flexibility, and proper bike fit
• Climbing, descending, sprinting, cornering, time trialing, attacking, bridging

EVENING PRESENTATIONS: A variety of USAC certified coaches, pro riders, and industry experts lend their expertise throughout camp by giving evening presentations.

More info:
Facebook Page: https://www.facebook.com/MarsHillCyclingCamp/
Webpage: https://marshillcycling.com/summer-camp/
directions: Directions to Camp: Our location is Dogwood Hall on the campus of Mars Hill University. From I-26 take exit 11. Go left at the stop sign or stoplight. Climb the hill to the first light at Main Street. Go through light and descend through campus, turning left onto Dormitory Rd. Take your first right and follow it around to the two-story brick building set at the base of the hill.

title: Hot Doggett
description:
Three Great Rides:
◾Doggett Mountain Challenge 100 mile
◾Devils Fork Metric Century
◾Big Laurel Grind 60 km

We will again be based on the beautiful Mars Hill University campus ( Directions to Mars Hill University )

Quiet scenic routes, challenging mountain climbs and screaming descents, well stocked rest stops, chip timing, awesome SAG support, free post-ride showers, post-ride meal, great “swag bags” including a commemorative t-shirt and more.
course: The Hot Doggett 100 event includes 3 great rides. The title event is a 100 mile tour through the mountains of Madison County North Carolina with 9600 feet of climbing. For a little less challenging ride there is the Devil's Fork Metric Century with 6200 feet of climbing.  Again this year, The Big Laurel Grind is a 60 kilometer ride for those who are not up to a full Metric Century  . See our website for more information.
notes: Ride amenities include showers, a post ride meal, ample parking, 7 well stocked rest stops, recorded times, low cost college dorm rooms and commemorative T shirts. All this plus the hospitality of Madison County
directions: Start/finish is located at 100 Athletic St. Mars Hill, NC 28754

title: Ride to the Rock
description:
Just like the 5K run, this event is unique in that athletes choose one or the other, but both races end with an intense 7-9% grade incline that finishes at the base of 315-foot-tall Chimney Rock.  Again, it’s your only chance to run or cycle up to Chimney Rock all year. 

The 25-Mile Bike event begins bright and early at 7:30 AM just outside the Chimney Rock Park entrance, traveling 22 miles. It starts east on 64/74A, turns left onto Bills Creek Road by the Library, left again onto Buffalo Creek Road by Dalton’s Store and eventually merges into Buffalo Shoals Road along Lake Lure’s eastern shore. It re-enters Route 64/74A with a right turn back to quaint Chimney Rock Village, where a left turn into the park entrance starts your last 3 epic miles straight up to Chimney Rock.
directions: Old Rock Cafe - 431 Main St, Chimney Rock, NC

title: DARC/AYC Juniors Skills Clinc
description: Saturday November 19 1-4PM at Carrier Park. For all juniors ages 9-18. USA Cycling Level 1 Coach Randy Warren will lead this Skills and Information Clinic. We will have Skills and Drills from 1-3PM and then from 3-4PM, refreshments and information about how the Asheville Youth Cycling and Downtown Asheville Racing Club (DARC) programs as they join under the DARC umbrella. All types of bicycles welcome (cross/mtb/bmx/road).
course: We will use the grass to the east of the Lawn Bowling Green in Carrier Park
registration: FREE to all juniors ages 9-18. All participants MUST fill out a USA Cycling Waiver/One Day License form or just a USAC Waiver if they have an Annual License. All fees for this clinic are being covered by DARC/AYC.
notes: This is a great opportunity for the juniors to work on bike handling and race skills as well as to let the juniors and their families know what the junior program will entail as we move forward into 2017.
